# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: stephen-silvagni
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] The station first broadcast on 29 November 1931 as 3AK.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] In October 2003, amid growing debt and struggling ratings, 3AK operators Data & Commerce Limited placed the station up for sale.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] In November, owners Data & Commerce Limited entered into a lease with the newly formed Sports Entertainment Network to create SEN 1116, a 24-hour sports radio station.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] Headed by managing director Danny Staffieri, formerly of FIVEaa, the new station was promoted as 'entertaining radio with a sports focus', and would rival horse racing station Sport 927.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] In the year's first radio ratings survey, the station jumped from reaching 1.2% of the Melbourne radio market as 3AK, to 2.1% as SEN, growing to 2.8% in the year's fourth survey despite the lack of coverage of any major sports.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] However, in July, the station secured broadcast rights to the 2004 Summer Olympics, alongside 2GB, 2CC, FIVEaa, 6IX, HO-FM and Hot 100, among others.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] SEN also carried coverage of the 2004 NRL Grand Final from 2GB, and the 2004–05 FA Premier League from BBC Radio 5 Live.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] In December 2004, the SEN brand was revealed to be expanded into Adelaide, with Sports Entertainment Network leasing news talk 5DN from Australian Radio Network to create **SEN 1323**.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] However, while the station remained flat in Melbourne, ratings dwindled in Adelaide; despite gaining coverage of the New Zealand cricket tour of Australia and the 2005 VFL season, Sports Entertainment Network entered voluntary administration, citing $3.5 million in losses.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] The SEN 1323 lease was cancelled, resulting in ARN launching easy listening-format Cruise 1323.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] The Melbourne station was sold back to Pacific Star Network, the renamed Data & Commerce Limited.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] In July 2015, the newsroom shared between SEN and sister station 3MP was closed, replaced with the Victorian news service from Macquarie National News, based at 3AW.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] In November 2015, it was announced that Francis Leach would depart ABC Grandstand Digital following the axing of the *Grandstand Breakfast* programme, and rejoin SEN, hosting *SEN Breakfast* alongside David Schwarz to replace *The Morning Glory*.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] Co-host Andrew Maher moved to afternoons, launching *SEN Lunch Break*, moving Daniel Harford into drive with Mark Allen.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] Andrew Gaze and Tim Watson, while losing regular timeslots, would remain with the station as a contributor.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] In January 2018, the station's schedule was again refreshed.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] Former ABC commentator Gerard Whateley joined the station as chief sports caller and mornings presenter, with Kevin Bartlett moving to the drive show following the departure of Harford.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] In April 2018, parent company Pacific Star Network merged with sports media business Crocmedia, most notable for producing the AFL Nation broadcast call heard across regional Australia.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] In July 2019, SEN has partnered with Crocmedia has purchased 23 narrowband radio licences across Australia including Sydney, Brisbane, Perth, Gold Coast, Darwin and Alice Springs.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] On 13 October 2018, SEN parent company Pacific Star Network confirmed it had purchased an AM narrowband licence in Adelaide, South Australia, returning the SEN brand to South Australia.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] The station launched on 1629 AM on 6 December 2018, with local presenters Kane Cornes, Andrew Hayes, Kym Dillon and Michelangelo Rucci.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] Other programs, including Gerard Whateley's morning show and live sports coverage, will be syndicated live from the Melbourne station.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] On 9 September 2019, *SEN SA Breakfast* commenced simulcasting on RadioTAB's 1539AM Adelaide frequency.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] On 2 December, a second South Australian frequency was launched – also on 1629 AM – covering Mount Gambier.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] SEN Track is a radio network broadcasting coverage of horse, thoroughbred and greyhound racing, which launched on 28 March 2020.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] 1170 SEN (official callsign 2CH) is a sports radio station in Sydney, New South Wales.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] On 17 October 2021 SEN Top End launched on 1611 AM Narrowcast broadcasting coverage of the Northern Territory Football League, horse, thoroughbred and greyhound racing.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] On 7 July 2021 SEN Hobart launched on 1629 AM Narrowcast providing coverage of several local and national sports such as Cricket, AFL, horse, thoroughbred and greyhound racing.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] There are live programs from Hobart on Friday, Saturday and Monday mornings.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] On the 3rd March 2021 SEN Gold Coast launched on 1620 AM Narrowcast providing coverage of several local and national sports such as Cricket, AFL, horse, thoroughbred and greyhound racing.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] SEN 1323 was launched on 1 February 2005 in Adelaide, replacing 5DN.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] It largely simulcast 1116 SEN, with a single opt-out program for the Adelaide market.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] The station closed following parent company Data & Commerce Limited entering voluntary administration in June 2005.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] SEN+ commenced broadcasting on 13 August 2018, replacing Classic Rock Radio.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] The station broadcast live coverage of the NFL, NBA, A-League and Super Rugby as well as live and timeshifted programming from the main SEN station.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] On 28 March 2020, it was replaced by SEN Track and has since been purchased by ACE Radio Broadcasters to relaunch as 3MP.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1116-sen] In February 2025, SEN sacked cricket journalist Peter Lalor for his social media posts about the Gaza genocide, with CEO Craig Hutchinson claiming that his posts "made Jewish people in Melbourne feel unsafe".
[src:stephen-silvagni/1985-vfl-season] The **1985 VFL season** was the 89th season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1985-vfl-season] The season featured twelve clubs, ran from 23 March until 28 September, and comprised a 22-game home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring the top five clubs.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1985-vfl-season] The season was the first to feature premiership matches on Friday nights.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1985-vfl-season] The premiership was won by the Essendon Football Club for the 14th time and second time consecutively, after it defeated Hawthorn by 78 points in the 1985 VFL Grand Final.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1986-vfl-season] The **1986 VFL season** was the 90th season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1986-vfl-season] The season featured twelve clubs, ran from 29 March until 27 September, and comprised a 22-game home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring the top five clubs.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1986-vfl-season] The premiership was won by the Hawthorn Football Club for the sixth time, after it defeated Carlton by 42 points in the 1986 VFL Grand Final.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1986-vfl-season] Hawthorn defeated Carlton 9.12 (66) to 5.6 (36) in the final.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] The **1987 VFL Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Carlton Football Club and Hawthorn Football Club, held at the Melbourne Cricket Ground in Melbourne on 26 September 1987.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] It was the 91st annual Grand Final of the Victorian Football League, staged to determine the premiers for the 1987 VFL season.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] The match, attended by 92,754 spectators, was won by Carlton by a margin of 33 points, marking that club's 15th premiership victory.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] At the conclusion of the home-and-away season, Carlton had finished first on the VFL ladder with 18 wins and 4 losses.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Those four losses were by a combined total of just 56 points.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] It had been a tumultuous year off the field for the Blues; premiership defender Des English was in an ongoing health battle since being diagnosed with leukemia the previous year, and rising star Peter Motley nearly lost his life in a serious car accident early in the season.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Hawthorn finished second, with 17 wins and 5 losses.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Carlton had only beaten Hawthorn in two of the last twelve games in which the two teams had met, although they had defeated them most recently in the Second-Semi Final leading up to the Grand Final.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] The Hawks had advanced to the Grand Final after defeating Sydney in the first Qualifying Final, and, after the Second-Semi Final, defeated Melbourne by just two points in the Preliminary Final (with a goal kicked after the final siren) to advance to the Grand Final.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] The Blues had an easier finals run, earning a weeks rest before the Second Semi Final and then advancing straight to the Grand Final after their Second-Semi Final win.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] It was Hawthorn's fifth successive Grand Final appearance and it had beaten Carlton in the previous season's Grand Final by 42 points.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Carlton had not won a flag since winning the 1982 VFL Grand Final.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] In the week leading up to the Grand Final, Hawthorn's John Platten was awarded the Brownlow Medal.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] The umpiring panel for the match, comprising two field umpires, two boundary umpires and two goal umpires is given below.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] The game was played on a very hot day, with temperatures reaching 30.7 °C or 87.3 °F.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] This broke the previous record for the hottest Grand Final day temperature set in 1944, and the record stood until 2015.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] The heat was thought to favour Carlton because Hawthorn had finished a very tough finals campaign.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] The Hawks were also deprived by an ankle injury of Jason Dunstall, who had kicked six goals against the Blues in the previous year's Grand Final and 94 for the 1987 season.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Paul Dear replaced Dunstall at full-forward.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Such was the heat that Stephen Silvagni, who for most of his career wore a long-sleeved guernsey, started the match without sleeves.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] It was also the only time in 426 games that Hawthorn captain Michael Tuck wore a sleeveless jumper, with he and Carlton's Mark Naley both starting the game wearing long sleeves and changing to short-sleeves part way through the game.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] In the pre-match festivities, the coin was tossed by Wimbledon champion and Hawks fan Pat Cash.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Michael Tuck won the toss and chose to kick to the City End.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Carlton were switched from the beginning when renowned finals specialist Wayne Johnston alerted umpire Ian Robinson (who was officiating in his ninth Grand final and final VFL game) that Hawthorn had one extra player in the centre square before the ball had been bounced.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Umpire Robinson blew the whistle to begin the game and promptly handed the ball to Johnston to take the free kick.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] His long kick into attack was marked strongly by Hunter 35 metres from goal directly in front, but he missed the opening shot at goal.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Carlton managed to retrieve possession from the kick-in, and Johnston was awarded another free kick for being tripped by Collins and duly converted his set shot for the first goal of the game.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Barely a minute later, Carlton went into attack again through Dennis and Dorotich but Meldrum was unable to finish accurately.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] The Hawks had their first score on the board when a snap from Schwab from a restart bounce in attack missed to the left.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] From the kick-in, Hawthorn's enforcer wingman DiPierdomenico collected the ball and was charging forward when Johnston caught him flush with an elbow to the jaw, for which he earned a report.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Carlton continued to struggle with accuracy when Naley's snap missed to the right, until finally Johnston picked up the ball after Schwab had lost it in a tackle and dashed forward before steadying and kicking truly on his trusty left foot for his second goal at the 12-minute mark.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] And when Hunter compensated for his early miss a few minutes later by converting his set shot from nearly the same position, Carlton had kicked three goals to set up a 20-point lead.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] But the battle-hardened Hawks were too experienced to panic.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Kennedy, who had been playing on Hunter, was moved forward and kicked Hawthorn's first, swooping on to a kick forward from Collins and snapping truly on his right as time-on began.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Platten and DiPierdomenico added further goals from set shots, and when Kennedy kicked his second after the quarter-time siren, the Hawks had grabbed a three-point lead, despite having been outplayed for much of the term.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Carlton again started strongly when Kernahan and Hunter combined to find Bradley in open space and running hard towards goal, enabling him to easily score his first for the game and restore Carlton's lead.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] At the 4-minute mark, Carlton added another goal after a grubby kick across the backline from Mew put Ayres under pressure from Meldrum, allowing Dorotich to pounce on the ball and kick his first.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] The Norm Smith Medal was presented by former Melbourne champion and premiership captain John Beckwith to Carlton's David Rhys-Jones.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Normally a wingman, he instead lined up in defence on Hawthorn's key forward Dermott Brereton in what many considered a mismatch.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Rhys-Jones only collected 17 disposals and four marks for the game (9 kicks, 8 handpasses); however, in keeping Brereton goalless for the only time in the 1987 season and marshalling his fellow defenders throughout the game, he was unanimously considered best on ground.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] It was sweet revenge for both Carlton and Rhys-Jones; in the previous season's Grand Final defeat, his direct opponent had been Gary Ayres, who went on to win the first of his two Norm Smith Medals.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] After the presentation of the premiership medals, Craig Bradley walked across to injured teammate Peter Motley, who had been left disabled following a car accident earlier in the year.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Bradley presented Motley with the premiership cup and his medal.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Just two months after the disappointment of losing the grand final, Hawthorn were dealt another blow when coach Allan Jeans was admitted to hospital with a brain haemorrhage.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] Although surgery to repair an aneurysm was successful, the health scare was serious enough to force Jeans to stand out of football for the whole of the 1988 VFL season.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] After not being picked for the grand final, club stalwart Rodney Eade left the club and went to Brisbane.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] However, Johnston and Madden had both been reported for striking.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] They would both miss the first two matches of the 1988 season.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-grand-final] After losing to Melbourne in the 1988 Preliminary Final, the Blues would not play in a grand final again until 1993.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-season] The **1987 VFL season** was the 91st season of the Victorian Football League (VFL).
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-season] The season ran from 27 March until 26 September, and comprised a 22-game home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring the top five clubs.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-season] The season saw the beginning of a decade-long period of expansion of the Victorian league to the rest of Australia, with the admission of two newly established clubs: the West Coast Eagles, based in Perth, Western Australia, and the Brisbane Bears, based in South East Queensland.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-season] While the league remained the highest level senior Australian rules football competition and administrative body in Victoria, it also became the *de facto* highest level senior competition in Australia, with representation across four states.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-season] In the pre-season, the first modern VFL draft was held.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-season] The premiership was won by the Carlton Football Club for the 15th time, after it defeated Hawthorn by 33 points in the 1987 VFL Grand Final.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-season] Melbourne defeated Essendon 8.10 (58) to 8.6 (54), to win the Night Series Grand Final at VFL Park.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-season] Rounds 16 and 17 were played concurrently over three weekends: five matches were played on the weekends of 11 and 18 July, and four matches were played on the weekend of 25 July.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-season] This fixturing effectively gave each team one bye during the three-week period.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-season] However, the matches are still grouped into two complete rounds rather than three partial rounds, which results in a chronological anomaly in which six teams played their Round 17 matches before their Round 16 matches.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-season] The final round of the 1987 VFL home-and-away season turned out to be one of the most dramatic and significant in VFL/AFL history.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-season] The round began on the Friday night with Richmond and the fledgling Brisbane Bears playing for the wooden spoon; the Bears won easily to ensure they didn't come last in their first season.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1987-vfl-season] The significant matches to determine the final five were all played on Saturday afternoon, and they were all thrillers.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1988-vfl-season] The season featured fourteen clubs, ran from 2 April until 24 September, and comprised a 22-game home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring the top five clubs.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1988-vfl-season] The premiership was won by the Hawthorn Football Club for the seventh time, after it defeated Melbourne by 96 points in the 1988 VFL Grand Final.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1988-vfl-season] Hawthorn 10.10 (70) defeated Geelong 9.13 (67) in the Night Series, which for the first time was played entirely as a pre-season competition, rather than a concurrent competition to the Premiership season.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1989-vfl-season] It was the last season under the Victorian Football League name, before being renamed the Australian Football League in 1990.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1989-vfl-season] The season featured fourteen clubs, ran from 31 March until 30 September, and comprised a 22-game home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring the top five clubs.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1989-vfl-season] The premiership was won by the Hawthorn Football Club for the eighth time and second time consecutively, after it defeated Geelong by six points in the 1989 VFL Grand Final.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1989-vfl-season] In addition, four of the clubs also played in an international exhibition offseason tournament in October with games in Toronto, Miami Gardens and London.
[src:stephen-silvagni/1989-vfl-season] 3. in Round 13, Essendon and Footscray played the lowest scoring game since the 1927 grand final, with the teams combining for only 6.15 (51) on a muddy Windy Hill.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] He is widely known by his nickname, "SOS" (pronounced "Soss"), standing for "Son of Serge", referring to his father, Sergio Silvagni, another great Carlton player.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] After retiring from playing, Silvagni has worked as an assistant coach and list manager at several AFL clubs.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] He is the former list manager of Carlton Football Club.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] On January 27, 2023, St Kilda Football Club confirmed the appointment of Stephen Silvagni as their new list manager.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] Silvagni was drafted to Carlton under the father–son rule, being the son of former Carlton Blues champion Sergio Silvagni and it was scarcely a surprise when he followed in his father's footsteps and made his Carlton debut, aged 17, in 1985.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] He is widely known by his nickname, "SOS" (pronounced "Soss"), standing for "Son of Serge", Silvagni was a highly energetic, resourceful footballer who was regarded as one of the finest full backs.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] He could also do a job in the forward lines, however, and some of his most memorable displays came after he was thrown into attack in an effort to bolster the team's performance.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] Silvagni's defensive skills were renowned and earned him the status as a true clubman at Carlton.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] In 1996's AFL Team of the Century, Silvagni had the honour of being named at full-back.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] Possibly his finest game was in the 1995 AFL Grand Final where he kept Geelong legend Gary Ablett goalless for the entire game.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] In addition to Silvagni's blanketing tactics, he was also a renowned high-flyer, taking out the Mark of the Year in 1988.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] However, when one such mark led to an ankle injury, the high-flying aspect of his game largely disappeared.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] Silvagni retired from his playing career at the end of the 2001 season, after he announced that he was taking specialist advice to call it a day after 16 seasons.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] A year after his retirement at the end of the 2001 season he announced that he would make a comeback to assist Carlton, following their penalties for salary cap infringements.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] He however changed his mind soon after and was not a listed player for the 2003 season.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] Silvagni also played as goalkeeper for the Australian International Rules team on several occasions, and won the inaugural Jim Stynes Medal in 1998.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] Silvagni played for Carlton Football Club from 1985 until 2001 for a total of 312 games and kicked a total of 202 goals.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] After retiring from playing, Silvagni worked as an assistant coach at six AFL clubs between 2002 and 2010: Collingwood, Sydney, Western Bulldogs and St Kilda.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] In 2011, Silvagni took on the role of list manager with the fledgling Greater Western Sydney Giants.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] He returned to Carlton as list manager in 2014.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] He was notably active in recruiting former GWS players to Carlton, with nine former GWS players shifting to Carlton in Silvagni's first three recruiting years.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] Stephen departed the Carlton Football Club, when he left his role as list manager on 4 December 2019, following the 2019 AFL season.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] Silvagni then described his tenure at the club as a "messy" situation because of the falling out with the club's management.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] On 27 January 2023, Silvagni was appointed to the role of list manager at St Kilda Football Club.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] Stephen Silvagni married television celebrity Jo Bailey in 1996, and they have three sons.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] Their eldest son Jack was drafted by Carlton in 2015.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] He played 128 games before transferring to St Kilda at the end of the 2025 season.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] Their second son, Ben, was also drafted by the Carlton Football Club in the 2018 AFL draft but was subsequently delisted after the 2020 season without having played a game.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] His third son is Tom Silvagni, who was convicted of rape in 2025, whose name was revealed after a lengthy suppression order was lifted.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] Since retiring from playing football he has worked in the media as a guest football commentator.
[src:stephen-silvagni/stephen-silvagni] Former Carlton Football Club key defender Alex Silvagni is Stephen's second cousin.
